posts.raw_content:
I recommend David to anyone who hasn't heard of it or who doesn't want to support bad studios.  This was an inspiring and uplifting kid's film which worked for adults as well.

It's a very abbreviated animated feature which spans from David's time as a shepherd up to his coronation as King.  So, the timeline is a little fudgy from a storytelling point of view.  He fights the lion, which leads to shepherding sheep, who lead him to Samuel in David's father's house, which leads to soldiers coming to get David and bring him before Saul, which leads to his friendship with Saul, then they look out the window and the Philistines are attacking.  Lol, so it doesn't do any "2 years later" time skipping, rather it tells the narrative kind of like a really long day with little transitions where you could assume time if you wanted to.  I don't think most people will notice that but I appreciated them just hitting the major beats of the story.

I did not know it would be a musical but for David's character it obviously makes sense that it would be a musical.  He breaks out into singing all the time, which is how he is in the Bible too.  I'd like to see which of the songs are derived from actual Psalms because there were a lot of lines which clearly were.

There is a montage transition when he switches to being an adult so he can be persecuted by Saul and fight the Amalekites.  The Amalekites are legitimately pretty creepy and designed very differently from the Philistines.

The focus on faith and reliance on God were very pleasing to see in a film.  Every situation is handled through the application of faith and gratitude.

There were moments I was wondering if the story would go there, such as David cutting off Goliath's head.  He isn't shown to do that, but the camera pans away from David standing over Goliath's body to follow the motion of the charging army instead (and the sword is just right there standing up from the ground prominently).  So if you know the story better you can see where they're not willing to switch away from it but rather just not make it the focus to keep it kid-friendly.

Probably the best two songs in my view were when his mother is singing about life and being fruitful while she takes him through the entire process from start to finish of making wool textiles from sheep wool.  They show every step of the process, without explaining it.  That was cool.  Apparently his siblings kept saying "mom is in there 'stress weaving' again" which my wife noticed but I missed.  She was weaving all the time.

It also did a good job of just showing things subtly to be accurate to the Bible without going into explanations of what everything was, so it didn't feel like it was trying to be a biblical primer or something.  It was just sticking to the story.
